"In
which
you
look
as
I
like
to
see
you,"
said
Shirley.
"You
are
a
lady
like
little
person,
Caroline.
Is
she
not,
Mrs.
Pryor?"
Mrs.
Pryor
never
paid
compliments,
and
seldom
indulged
in
remarks,
favourable
or
otherwise,
on
personal
appearance.
On
the
present
occasion
she
only
swept
Caroline's
curls
from
her
cheek
as
she
took
a
seat
near
her,
caressed
the
oval
outline,
and
observed,
"You
get
somewhat
thin,
my
love,
and
somewhat
pale.
Do
you
sleep
well?
your
eyes
have
a
languid
look."
And
she
gazed
at
her
anxiously.
"I
sometimes
dream
melancholy
dreams,"
answered
Caroline;
"and
if
I
lie
awake
for
an
hour
or
two
in
the
night,
I
am
continually
thinking
of
the
rectory
as
a
dreary
old
place.
You
know
it
is
very
near
the
churchyard.
The
back
part
of
the
house
is
extremely
ancient,
and
it
is
said
that
the
out
kitchens
there
were
once
enclosed
in
the
churchyard,
and
that
there
are
graves
under
them.
I
rather
long
to
leave
the
rectory."
"My
dear,
you
are
surely
not
superstitious?"
"No,
Mrs.
Pryor;
but
I
think
I
grow
what
is
called
nervous.
I
see
things
under
a
darker
aspect
than
I
used
to
do.
I
have
fears
I
never
used
to
have
not
of
ghosts,
but
of
omens
and
disastrous
events;
and
I
have
an
inexpressible
weight
on
